value.value: Binding to a tetratricopeptide repeat (TPR) domain of a protein, the consensus sequence of which is defined by a pattern of small and large hydrophobic amino acids and a structure composed of helices.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a deep water stimulus, being immersed in standing deep water throughout the life cycle.

definition.value: Note that this term should not be confused with 'response to flooding ; GO:0009413'; which refers to immersion in water on a shorter time scale.

value.value: Formation of the junction between an axon and the glial cell that forms the myelin sheath. Paranodal junctions form at each paranode, i.e. at the ends of the unmyelinated nodes of Ranvier.

A conserved complex that contains a heterodimer of SMC proteins (Smc5p and Smc6p, or homologs thereof) and several other proteins, and is involved in DNA repair and maintaining cell cycle arrest following DNA damage. In S. cerevisiae, this is an octameric complex called Mms21-Smc5-Smc6 complex, with at least five of its subunits conserved in fission yeast and humans.
The process resulting in the transition of the otic placode into the otic vesicle, a transient embryonic structure formed during development of the vertebrate inner ear.

The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the midbrain-hindbrain boundary over time, from its formation to the mature structure. The midbrain-hindbrain domain of the embryonic brain is comprised of the mesencephalic vesicle and the first rhombencephalic vesicle at early somitogenesis stages.
The acetylation of peptidyl-serine to form peptidyl-O-acetyl-L-serine.
The acetylation of peptidyl-serine.

Complex that possesses ADPG pyrophosphorylase activity. In all organisms where it has been found, the complex is a tetramer. In bacteria, it is a homotetramer. In plants, the complex is a heterotetramer composed small and large subunits.
A protein complex composed of four identical subunits that possesses ADPG pyrophosphorylase activity. Examples of this component are found in Bacterial species.
A protein complex composed of four different subunits that possesses ADPG pyrophosphorylase activity. An example of this process is found in Mus musculus.
An ADPG pyrophosphorylase complex found in the amyloplast.
An ADPG pyrophosphorylase complex found in the chloroplast.
Any collagen complex which links one collagen assembly, such as a collagen fibril or sheet, to other structures.
A protein complex consisting of three collagen chains assembled into a left-handed triple helix. These trimers assemble into a sheet.
Any collagen trimer that passes through a lipid bilayer membrane.
A collagen homotrimer of alpha1(XVII) chains; type XVII collagen triple helices span the plasma membrane and associate with hemidesmosomes and the basal lamina where they bind laminin.
A collagen homotrimer of alpha1(XVIII) chains.
Binding to a chloroplast targeting sequence, a specific peptide sequence that acts as a signal to localize the protein within the chloroplast.
Binding to an endoplasmic reticulum signal peptide, a specific peptide sequence that acts as a signal to localize the protein within the endoplasmic reticulum.
Binding to a mitochondrion targeting sequence, a specific peptide sequence that acts as a signal to localize the protein within the mitochondrion.
Binding to a KDEL sequence, the C terminus tetrapeptide sequence Asp-Asp-Glu-Leu found in proteins that are to be retained in the endoplasmic reticulum.
Catalysis of the reaction: protein tyrosine phosphate + H2O = protein tyrosine + phosphate. This reaction requires metal ions.

label.value: regulation of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

label.value: negative regulation of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

label.value: positive regulation of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of vascular endothelial growth factor receptor signaling pathway activity.

label.value: establishment or maintenance of actin cytoskeleton polarity

value.value: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of polarized actin-based cytoskeletal structures.

label.value: establishment or maintenance of microtubule cytoskeleton polarity

value.value: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of polarized microtubule-based cytoskeletal structures.

label.value: establishment or maintenance of cytoskeleton polarity

value.value: Any cellular process that results in the specification, formation or maintenance of polarized cytoskeletal structures.

A process that is carried out at the cellular level which results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of astral microtubules, any of the spindle microtubules that radiate in all directions from the spindle poles.
The 'de novo' formation of an astral microtubule, in which tubulin heterodimers form metastable oligomeric aggregates, some of which go on to support formation of a complete microtubule.
Binding to a potassium ion (K+).

A protein complex that possesses glutamyl-tRNA(Gln) amidotransferase activity, and therefore creates Gln-tRNA by amidating Glu-tRNA; usually composed of 3 subunits: A, B, and C. Note that the C subunit may not be required in all organisms.

definition.value: Note that this term represents a location and not a function; the activity possessed by this complex is mentioned in the definition for the purpose of describing and distinguishing the complex. The function possessed by this complex is represented by the molecular function term 'glutaminyl-tRNA synthase (glutamine-hydrolyzing) activity ; GO:0050567'.

value.value: Binding to Tat, a viral transactivating regulatory protein from the human immunodeficiency virus, or the equivalent protein from another virus.

A protein complex required for heterochromatin assembly; contains an Argonaute homolog, a chromodomain protein, and at least one additional protein; named for RNA-induced initiation of transcriptional gene silencing.
The hydroxylation of peptidyl-arginine to form peptidyl-hydroxyarginine.

An integral membrane complex that possesses NADH oxidoreductase activity. The complex is one of the components of the electron transport chain. It catalyzes the transfer of a pair of electrons from NADH to a quinone.

definition.value: Note that this term represents a location and not a function; the activity possessed by this complex is mentioned in the definition for the purpose of describing and distinguishing the complex. The function possessed by this complex is represented by the molecular function term 'NADH dehydrogenase (quinone) activity ; GO:0050136'.

label.value: plasma membrane electron transport, NADH to quinone

value.value: The transfer of electrons from NADH to the quinone pool that occurs during oxidative phosphorylation and results in the generation of a proton gradient, mediated by the enzyme known as NADH-quinone oxidoreductase.

The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the presence of unfolded proteins in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) or other ER-related stress; results in changes in the regulation of transcription and translation.

definition.value: Note that this term should not be confused with 'response to unfolded protein ; GO:0006986', which refers to any response to the presence of unfolded proteins anywhere in the cell or in multicellular organism.

label.value: retrograde protein transport, ER to cytosol

value.value: The directed movement of unfolded or misfolded proteins from the endoplasmic reticulum to the cytosol through the translocon.
Binding to a receptor that possesses protein tyrosine kinase activity.
Binding to a molybdate ion (MoO4 2-).
The process in which thiamine pyrophosphate is transported across a membrane.
Binding to thiamine (vitamin B1), a water soluble vitamin present in fresh vegetables and meats, especially liver.
Binding to thiamine pyrophosphate, the diphosphoric ester of thiamine. Acts as a coenzyme of several (de)carboxylases, transketolases, and alpha-oxoacid dehydrogenases.
Binding to taurine.
The chemical reactions and pathways involving alpha-glucans, compounds composed of glucose residues linked by alpha-D-glucosidic bonds.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of alpha-glucans, compounds composed of glucose residues linked by alpha-D-glucosidic bonds.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of alpha-glucans.
The portion of the microtubule cytoskeleton that lies just beneath the plasma membrane.
